Timbuctoo REST API documentation

This specification describes the workings of the v2.1 version of the Timbuctoo REST API. It is authored as an [[html-polyglot]] document.

Authentication

Preface

This specification describes the workings of the v2.1 version of the Timbuctoo REST API for authentication.

Local login

For local login HTTP Basic Authorization is used.
Request:
POST /v2.1/authenticate HTTP/1.1
Authorization: Basic dXNlcjpwYXNzd29yZA==
Response:
HTTP/1.1 204 No Content
access-control-expose-headers: Location, Link, X_AUTH_TOKEN //not part of contract
access-control-allow-origin: * //not part of contract
access-control-allow-methods: GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, OPTIONS, HEAD //not part of contract
access-control-allow-credentials: true //not part of contract
x_auth_token: 1ba1e769-4f01-4e23-bc01-2a5b1fd60ec8 //is provided
access-control-allow-headers: origin, content-type, accept, authorization, vre_id //not part of contract
date: Thu, 21 Apr 2016 14:16:34 GMT //not part of contract
You then get a X_AUTH_TOKEN header back (In this case 1ba1e769-4f01-4e23-bc01-2a5b1fd60ec8) that you can use to get your own user information.
If you use a wrong user password combination, the response will be 401 Unauthorized.
If the request does not contain a 'Authorization' header, the response will be 401 Unauthorized.

Get user information

Request:
GET /v2.1/system/users/me HTTP/1.1
Authorization: 1ba1e769-4f01-4e23-bc01-2a5b1fd60ec8
VRE_ID: WomenWriters
Response:
HTTP/1.1 200 OK
access-control-expose-headers: Location, Link, X_AUTH_TOKEN //not part of contract
access-control-allow-origin: * //not part of contract
access-control-allow-methods: GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, OPTIONS, HEAD //not part of contract
access-control-allow-credentials: true //not part of contract
content-length: 96 //not part of contract
access-control-allow-headers: origin, content-type, accept, authorization, vre_id //not part of contract
date: Thu, 21 Apr 2016 14:16:34 GMT //not part of contract
content-type: application/json //not part of contract

{
  "persistentId": "pid", //not part of contract
  "@type": "user", //not part of contract
  "displayName": "givenName surname", //is a string
  "_id": "USER000000000001", //not part of contract
}
Results generated by Concordion
in 550 ms on 21-Apr-2016 at 16:16:34 CEST

Faceted Search

Preface

Timbuctoo has support for building faceted searches. Doing a faceted search usually follows the following steps.
  1. You retrieve facets by performing an empty POST to the search endpoint, and GET the returned location
  2. You present the returned facets to the user
  3. The user selects some combination of facets
  4. You search using the selected facets
  5. You present the returned results to the user and update your facet list based on the new facets
  6. The user updates its combination of facets
  7. etc.

Retrieving facets

Let's assume we're searching the collection wwpersons.
Request:
POST /v2.1/search/wwpersons HTTP/1.1
VRE_ID: WomenWriters
Content-type: application/json

{}
Response:
HTTP/1.1 201 Created
access-control-expose-headers: Location, Link, X_AUTH_TOKEN //not part of contract
access-control-allow-origin: * //not part of contract
access-control-allow-methods: GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, OPTIONS, HEAD //not part of contract
access-control-allow-credentials: true //not part of contract
content-length: 0 //not part of contract
access-control-allow-headers: origin, content-type, accept, authorization, vre_id //not part of contract
date: Thu, 21 Apr 2016 14:20:51 GMT //not part of contract
location: http://localhost:8089/v2.1/search/ec2c7458-e62c-42bc-9384-8a801c6d067e //is provided
A request for search to an unknown collection will result in a 400 Bad Request

You then get a Location header back (In this case http://localhost:8089/v2.1/search/ec2c7458-e62c-42bc-9384-8a801c6d067e) that contains a fully qualified HTTP url. This url is valid during the next few hours. Once it starts returning 404's you are expected to retry the POST.

Request: (to http://localhost:8089)
GET /v2.1/search/ec2c7458-e62c-42bc-9384-8a801c6d067e HTTP/1.1
Response:
HTTP/1.1 200 OK
transfer-encoding: chunked //not part of contract
access-control-expose-headers: Location, Link, X_AUTH_TOKEN //not part of contract
access-control-allow-origin: * //not part of contract
access-control-allow-methods: GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, OPTIONS, HEAD //not part of contract
access-control-allow-credentials: true //not part of contract
vary: Accept-Encoding //not part of contract
access-control-allow-headers: origin, content-type, accept, authorization, vre_id //not part of contract
date: Thu, 21 Apr 2016 14:20:59 GMT //not part of contract
content-type: application/json //not part of contract

When a GET request is done with a malformed UUID, 400 Bad Request is returned.
When a an unknown search result is requested, 404 Not Found is returned.
  • numFound contains the total number of records that match the query and is therefore always greater than , or equal to the facet numbers and the rows property.
  • start contains the offset, in items
  • rows contains the amount of rows in the returned dataset.
    • This is always equal to the length of the refs array.
    • Might be less then 10 when the resultset contains less then 10 items.
  • _next contains a fully qualified url to the next results, if there are next results.
  • _prev contains a fully qualified url to the previous results, if there are previous results.
  • sortableFields is an array of names of sort parameters.
  • sortableFields is an collections of names that can be used as sort parameters.
  • fullTextSearchFields contains the names of the fields that can be used for full text search.

Facets

Timbuctoo supports two types of facets. A general facet could contain the following values in the type property:
  • BOOLEAN, has 2 options with the names true and false.
  • LIST, has a list with of options with unpredictable names and has an unpredictable length.
        {
          "name": "facet name",
          "type": "(possible values described above)",
          "options": [
            {
               "name": "option1",
               "count": 1176
            },
            {
               "name": "option2",
               "count": 126
            },
          ]
        }
The ranges facets are used to search on date ranges. They have one option with an upperLimit and a lowerLimit. The values are date converted to a number. The format is yyyyMMdd years after the first millennium. Years after the first century will have the format yyyMMdd. So only the MM and dd part of the format is ensured. The years part could be as little as one y. 
        {
          "name": "facet name",
          "type": "RANGE",
          "options": [{
            "upperLimit": 20150204,
            "lowerLimit": 20120114
          }]
        }

Refs

Each ref consists of 3 fields. The datafield contains no fields that describe the entity. The displayName contains a simple display name. The path contains a relative path to the complete entity. 
        {
          "data": {},
          "displayName": "Name",
          "path": "path/to/entity"
        }

Query parameters

In the get request above no query parameters are used. The search requests supports two query paramters
  • rows
    • Defines the maximum number of results that are returned.
    • Has as default value 10.
  • start
    • Defines the offset of the search result
    • Has as default value 0.

Searching with the selected facets

You can use the information in the facets, sortableFields and fullTextSearchFields to create a query form. You can use the information createResponse the refs property to show a set of results.

The form should then create a POST containing those facets and fulltext fields that you wish to filter on. Let's use a different domain (charterportaal) for our next search.

Request:
POST /v2.1/search/wwpersons HTTP/1.1
VRE_ID: WomenWriters
Content-type: application/json

{
  "facetValues":[
    {"name": "dynamic_s_gender","values":["FEMALE"]},
    {"name": "dynamic_s_residence","values":["France"]},
    {"name": "dynamic_s_language","values":["English"]},
    {"name": "dynamic_s_marital_status","values":["Widowed"]}
  ]
}
Response:
HTTP/1.1 201 Created
access-control-expose-headers: Location, Link, X_AUTH_TOKEN //not part of contract
access-control-allow-origin: * //not part of contract
access-control-allow-methods: GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, OPTIONS, HEAD //not part of contract
access-control-allow-credentials: true //not part of contract
content-length: 0 //not part of contract
access-control-allow-headers: origin, content-type, accept, authorization, vre_id //not part of contract
date: Thu, 21 Apr 2016 14:20:59 GMT //not part of contract
location: http://localhost:8089/v2.1/search/18b2f773-13e6-4801-8a9a-34d024584a65 //is provided
Request: (to http://localhost:8089)

The example above shows how to search with list facets. The search with date facets is a bit different. The facet will look like the example below. The upper and lower limit have number representation of a date string with the format 'yyyyMMdd'. 
          {
            "name": "facet name",
            "lowerLimit":12505560,
            "upperLimit":19301231
          }

Reception search

Preface

Timbuctoo 2.1 can start a relation search using a faceted search ID as starting point.

Currently The only implemented use cases are a search for receptions (in the form of wwdocuments) on:

  • wwpersons
  • wwdocuments

For this test we assume an existing wwpersons search ID: e3efaa4d-1f90-4681-91bf-0deaf8eb3d45.

Performing reception search on wwpersons

When you POST the wwpersons search ID to the relation search with wwdocuments to start the reception search on persons.
Request:
POST /v2.1/search/wwrelations/wwdocuments HTTP/1.1
VRE_ID: WomenWriters
Content-type: application/json

{
  "otherSearchId": "e3efaa4d-1f90-4681-91bf-0deaf8eb3d45"
}
Response:
HTTP/1.1 201 Created
access-control-expose-headers: Location, Link, X_AUTH_TOKEN //not part of contract
access-control-allow-origin: * //not part of contract
access-control-allow-methods: GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, OPTIONS, HEAD //not part of contract
access-control-allow-credentials: true //not part of contract
content-length: 0 //not part of contract
access-control-allow-headers: origin, content-type, accept, authorization, vre_id //not part of contract
date: Thu, 21 Apr 2016 14:18:01 GMT //not part of contract
location: http://localhost:8089/v2.1/search/413e7056-afc2-4d05-bfdf-73ffe8a03582 //is provided

You get a Location header back (In this case http://localhost:8089/v2.1/search/413e7056-afc2-4d05-bfdf-73ffe8a03582) that contains a fully qualified HTTP url. This url is valid during the next few hours. Once it starts returning 404's you are expected to retry the POST.

WWCollective

Preface

This specification describes the workings of the v2.1 version of the Timbuctoo REST API for wwdocuments

For each test we expect the user is logged in and uses token 98b5edf9-c84d-47fe-84df-f1c965c670f9.

Create a new wwcollective with POST

When a valid POST is performed to wwcollectives

Request:
POST /v2.1/domain/wwcollectives HTTP/1.1
Authorization: 98b5edf9-c84d-47fe-84df-f1c965c670f9
Content-type: application/json
VRE_ID: WomenWriters

{
  "@type": "wwcollective",
  "type": "ACADEMY",
  "name": "Testcollective",
  "links": [{
      "url": "http://example.com",
      "label": "Test link"
  }]
}

The server will respond with a location header containing the URL of the created resource

Response:
HTTP/1.1 201 Created
access-control-expose-headers: Location, Link, X_AUTH_TOKEN //not part of contract
access-control-allow-origin: * //not part of contract
access-control-allow-methods: GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, OPTIONS, HEAD //not part of contract
access-control-allow-credentials: true //not part of contract
content-length: 0 //not part of contract
access-control-allow-headers: origin, content-type, accept, authorization, vre_id //not part of contract
date: Thu, 21 Apr 2016 14:19:15 GMT //not part of contract
location: http://localhost:8089/v2.1/domain/wwcollectives/ae066c70-f76d-4c3f-b258-6f044a1e8e59 //is provided

The field type should have one of these values:

  • UNKNOWN
  • ACADEMY
  • ASSOCIATION
  • LIBRARY
  • PUBLISHER
  • SHOP

After at most 60 seconds the new record should have persistent ID in the field ^pid: URL .

Deleting a wwcollective

When a DELETE is sent to an existing wwcollective resource

Request: (to http://localhost:8089)
DELETE /v2.1/domain/wwcollectives/ae066c70-f76d-4c3f-b258-6f044a1e8e59 HTTP/1.1
Authorization: 98b5edf9-c84d-47fe-84df-f1c965c670f9
VRE_ID: WomenWriters

The server will respond with statusCode 204 no content

Response:
HTTP/1.1 204 No Content
access-control-expose-headers: Location, Link, X_AUTH_TOKEN //not part of contract

WWDocument

Preface

This specification describes the workings of the v2.1 version of the Timbuctoo REST API for wwdocuments

For each test we expect the user is logged in and uses token 92871b85-5de6-4234-bde3-5b35da374716.

Create a new wwdocument with POST

When a valid POST is performed to wwdocuments

Request:
POST /v2.1/domain/wwdocuments HTTP/1.1
Authorization: 92871b85-5de6-4234-bde3-5b35da374716
Content-type: application/json
VRE_ID: WomenWriters

{
  "@type": "wwdocument",
  "documentType": "PERIODICAL",
  "englishTitle": "English title",
  "title": "Title",
  "date": "1850",
  "reference": "A reference",
  "notes": "A note",
  "links": [{
    "url": "http://example.com",
    "label": "Test link"
  }]
}

The server will respond with a location header containing the URL of the created resource

Response:
HTTP/1.1 201 Created
access-control-expose-headers: Location, Link, X_AUTH_TOKEN //not part of contract
access-control-allow-origin: * //not part of contract
access-control-allow-methods: GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, OPTIONS, HEAD //not part of contract
access-control-allow-credentials: true //not part of contract
content-length: 0 //not part of contract
access-control-allow-headers: origin, content-type, accept, authorization, vre_id //not part of contract
date: Thu, 21 Apr 2016 14:20:19 GMT //not part of contract
location: http://localhost:8089/v2.1/domain/wwdocuments/ef45c78f-e371-405c-aa29-8945a20c7395 //is provided

The field documentType should have one of these values:

  • UNKNOWN
  • ANTHOLOGY
  • ARTICLE
  • AWARD
  • CATALOGUE
  • COMPILATION
  • DIARY
  • LETTER
  • LIST
  • MONOGRAPH
  • PERIODICAL
  • PICTURE
  • PUBLICITY
  • SHEETMUSIC
  • THEATERSCRIPT
  • WORK

The field resourceType is currently not used by the frontend but should be one of these values:

  • UNKNOWN
  • IMAGE
  • SOUND
  • TEXT
It will now default to UNKNOWN

After at most 60 seconds the new record should have persistent ID in the field ^pid: URL .

WWRelation

This specification describes the workings of the v2.1 version of the Timbuctoo REST API for wwrelations

For each test we expect the user is logged in and uses token 46c25c26-792f-4533-b856-013639406fd0.

And we assume an existing wwdocument with this id: 6fbe30dc-30d5-4d95-a336-cf7f5043d05e.

And we assume an existing wwperson with this id: 3edc61b6-642d-4cbe-a072-d9103191e88c.

And we will use the relation "isCreatedBy" which has the id: 4d139c1d-d6c7-48dc-82ec-174c67908d5b.

Create a new wwrelation with POST

When a valid POST is performed to wwrelations

Request:
POST /v2.1/domain/wwrelations HTTP/1.1
Authorization: 46c25c26-792f-4533-b856-013639406fd0
Content-type: application/json
VRE_ID: WomenWriters

{
  "accepted": true,
  "@type": "wwrelation",
  "^typeId":"4d139c1d-d6c7-48dc-82ec-174c67908d5b",
  "^sourceId":"6fbe30dc-30d5-4d95-a336-cf7f5043d05e",
  "^sourceType":"document",
  "^targetId":"3edc61b6-642d-4cbe-a072-d9103191e88c",
  "^targetType":"person"
}

The server will respond with a location header containing the URL of the created resource

Response:
HTTP/1.1 201 Created
access-control-expose-headers: Location, Link, X_AUTH_TOKEN //not part of contract
access-control-allow-origin: * //not part of contract
access-control-allow-methods: GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, OPTIONS, HEAD //not part of contract
access-control-allow-credentials: true //not part of contract
content-length: 0 //not part of contract
access-control-allow-headers: origin, content-type, accept, authorization, vre_id //not part of contract
date: Thu, 21 Apr 2016 14:22:16 GMT //not part of contract
location: http://localhost:8089/v2.1/domain/wwrelations/f18fb923-f8e1-4119-9a36-0a6b37f37f8b //is provided

After at most 60 seconds the new record should have persistent ID in the field ^pid: URL .

When we GET the wwdocument

The wwperson should have a @relationCount of 1 and an isCreatedBy relation in @relations to the wwperson

HTTP/1.1 200 OK
